the Christian Discourse of Early Written Latvian -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis multi- and cross-lingual collection of articles charts the influence of the Lutheran Reformation on various Northern European languages and texts written in them. While there are many studies on the internal developments of individual languages during the Reformation, very little has been written about influences between these languages. Mobility, networks of texts, knowledge and authors, and the exchange of ideas and the spread of reformatory thought belong to the topics of the present volume. The articles look into language use, language culture, and translation activities during the Reformation, but also leading to the Reformation as well as following from it later on in the Early Modern period. The contributors are experts in the study of their respective languages, including Czech, Danish, Dutch, English, Estonian, Finnish, High German, Icelandic, Latvian, Lithuanian, Low German, Polish and Swedish. The primary texts explored in the articles include Bible translations, hymns and other printed or handwritten materials.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aEarly Modern Period. 4aHistory. 4aLanguage and Linguistics. 4aTheology and Religion. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aTextual culture of the Lutheran Reformation, Early Modern period, language contacts, translation.1 aBentlin, Mikko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDittmann, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlood, John L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFonsén, Tuomo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKauko, Mikko, eeditor.4edt4http://i